In this article, President Barack Obama proclaims October as National Domestic Violence Awareness Month in the United States. He acknowledges the progress made in addressing domestic violence since the passage of the Violence Against Women Act (VAWA) nearly 20 years ago, but also highlights the ongoing issue of domestic violence. He emphasizes the need for continued efforts to protect and provide justice for survivors and to prevent violence from occurring. The President mentions various initiatives and policies implemented to combat domestic violence, including grants, the Violence Against Women Reauthorization Act, and provisions under the Affordable Care Act. He encourages individuals to stand against domestic violence, support victims, and promote peace in families and communities. The article concludes with the official proclamation of National Domestic Violence Awareness Month for October 2013.